      <div xml:id="NA169-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu viṉaimuṟṟi maṟuttarāniṉṟā (EV: mīḷun talaivaṉ taṉ) ṉeñciṟku uraittatu (ET: colliyatu).</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what [HE] said to [his] heart that kept refusing after havibg finished work.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA169">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            muṉṉiya muṭittaṉa māyi ṉaṉṉutal</l>
<l>            varuva meṉṉum paruvara ṟīrap</l>
<l>            paṭuṅkol vāḻi neṭuñcuvarp palli</l>
<l>            paraṟṟalaip pōkiya ciraṟṟalaik kaḷḷi</l>
<l>            mīmicaik kalitta vīnaṟu mullai </l>
<l>            yāṭutalait turuviṉ ṟōṭutalaip peyarkkum</l>
<l>            vaṉkai yiṭaiya ṉellip parīi</l>
<l>            veṇpōḻ taiiya valaṅkalan toṭalai</l>
<l>            maṟukuṭaṉ kamaḻu mālaic</l>
<l>            ciṟukuṭip pākkattem perunaka rāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Will a gecko appear – live – on the long wall</l>
<l rend="indent">to end the suffering by saying</l>
<l rend="indent3">“we will come,</l>
<l rend="indent2">[you of] good forehead, when [our] plans are completed”,</l>
<l>– in our big mansion in the village of small homes,</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the evening when swaying pretty garlands emit fragrance</l>
<l rend="indent2">in all the streets, knitted from white palmyra leaves(?),</l>
<l rend="indent">swept together<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">parīi</term>: actually, an absolutive instead of a peyareccam is difficult to construe, but the infinitive of the variants is in no way better. Apart from that the precise meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">paruvu</term> is unclear.</note> at daytime by the strong-handed herdsman,</l>
<l rend="indent">who recovers the herds of sheep with moving(?)<note place="foot">What is the impact of <term xml:lang="ta">āṭu</term> here? In any case it is part of a half-line formula to be found also in AN 274.4 (AN 394.13 reads <term xml:lang="ta">āṭu talaip peyarkkum</term>).</note> heads,</l>
<l rend="indent3">with the jasmine fragrant with blossoms that flourished on the</l>
<l rend="indent3">heights of spurges with kingfisher[-like] heads, gone over</l>
<l rend="indent4">the pebble-heads(?)<note place="foot">The exact syntax and impact of lines 4-6, with its double repetition of <term xml:lang="ta">talai</term> in lines 4 and 6, is unclear. Or is the first to be taken as a locative suffix?</note>?</l>
        </lg>
